---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';

const faq = [
  {
    question: "How do I check which npm packages are outdated?",
    answer: "Run npm outdated in your project directory. It outputs a table showing current version, the version your package.json range allows (Wanted), and the Latest published version. To update to wanted versions automatically: npm update. To update to latest (potentially breaking) versions: npx npm-check-updates -u && npm install. Always read the changelog before accepting a major version bump."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the difference between Dependabot and Renovate?",
    answer: "Dependabot is GitHub's built-in dependency update bot — simple to enable (one .github/dependabot.yml file), free, and integrated into GitHub's security dashboard. Renovate (Mend) is more configurable: it supports grouping related packages into a single PR, custom schedules, automerge for patch/minor, monorepo support, and over 60 package managers. For straightforward npm/pip projects, Dependabot is sufficient. For large codebases or complex update strategies, Renovate's additional flexibility is worth the setup cost."
  },
  {
    question: "Should I always update to the latest version?",
    answer: "No. Patch updates (1.2.3 → 1.2.4) are generally safe to accept without review — they are bug fixes. Minor updates (1.2.3 → 1.3.0) should be tested but rarely break things if you follow semver. Major updates (1.x.x → 2.0.0) require reading the migration guide — they contain intentional breaking changes. Automate minor/patch updates via Renovate's automerge after your CI passes. Always manually review major updates."
  },
  {
    question: "How do I check outdated Python packages?",
    answer: "Run pip list --outdated to see all packages with available updates. For interactive updating, use pip-review: pip install pip-review && pip-review --interactive. For automated CI updates, pip-audit combines outdated detection with vulnerability scanning. In poetry projects, use poetry show --outdated. For requirements.txt pinning, pip-compile (from pip-tools) regenerates the pinned lockfile from your high-level requirements.in file."
  },
  {
    question: "What does a semver range like ^1.2.3 or ~1.2.3 mean?",
    answer: "The ^ (caret) prefix allows updates to any non-breaking version: ^1.2.3 matches >=1.2.3 <2.0.0. It is npm's default and is appropriate for most dependencies. The ~ (tilde) prefix is more conservative: ~1.2.3 matches >=1.2.3 <1.3.0 — only patch updates. Use ~ for dependencies with a history of minor breaking changes. Use exact versions (no prefix) for critical infrastructure dependencies where you want explicit control over every update."
  },
  {
    question: "How do I set up Dependabot for automated security updates?",
    answer: "Create .github/dependabot.yml in your repository. Set package-ecosystem (npm, pip, docker, github-actions), directory ('/'), and schedule (daily, weekly, monthly). Dependabot automatically opens PRs for security vulnerabilities (free on all plans) and version updates (requires configuration). For security-only mode without version update noise, use Security updates in GitHub Settings → Code security and analysis without a dependabot.yml file."
  }
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Dependency Update Checker: npm, pip & gem Outdated Package Guide"
  description="Keep dependencies up to date and secure. Covers npm outdated, pip-review, Dependabot setup, Renovate Bot config, semver range strategies, and major vs minor update risk assessment."
  tool="dependency updates, npm outdated, pip-review, Dependabot, Renovate, outdated packages, semver range"
  faq={faq}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"WebPage","name":"Dependency Update Checker: npm, pip & gem Outdated Package Guide","url":"https://devplaybook.cc/tools/dependency-update-checker","description":"Complete guide to checking and automating dependency updates for npm, pip, and other package managers using Dependabot and Renovate."})} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Dependency Update Checker: npm, pip & Outdated Package Guide</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">Outdated dependencies are one of the leading sources of security vulnerabilities and compatibility issues in production software. This guide covers how to audit outdated packages across npm, pip, and other ecosystems — and how to automate the update process with Dependabot and Renovate so staying current requires no manual effort.</p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> npm outdated &amp; update commands</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> pip-review &amp; pip-audit</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Dependabot setup guide</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Renovate Bot configuration</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Major vs minor update risk table</span>
  </div>

  <ToolPageCta />

  <div class="mt-8 space-y-8">

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3">Checking Outdated npm Packages</h2>
      <p class="text-text-muted mb-4"><code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">npm outdated</code> gives you a clear picture of what is behind. Use <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">npm-check-updates</code> to automatically update your <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">package.json</code> to the latest compatible versions.</p>
      <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm font-mono text-gray-300"><code># Check outdated packages
npm outdated
# Output:
# Package         Current  Wanted  Latest  Location
# react           17.0.2   17.0.2  18.2.0  my-app
# typescript       4.9.5    4.9.5   5.3.2  my-app
# eslint           7.32.0   7.32.0  8.55.0  my-app

# Update to semver-compatible versions (respects ^ and ~ in package.json)
npm update

# Check what npm-check-updates would change (dry run)
npx npm-check-updates

# Apply all updates to package.json (then npm install to apply)
npx npm-check-updates -u && npm install

# Update only patch and minor (skip major version bumps)
npx npm-check-updates --target minor -u && npm install

# Check for security vulnerabilities separately
npm audit
npm audit fix             # auto-fix low-risk vulnerabilities
npm audit fix --force     # also fix breaking-change security fixes</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3">Python Dependency Auditing</h2>
      <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">For Python projects, combine <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">pip list --outdated</code> for a quick overview with <code class="font-mono text-sm bg-bg-card px-1 rounded">pip-audit</code> for security scanning. Poetry and pip-tools users have dedicated commands that maintain lockfile integrity.</p>
      <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm font-mono text-gray-300"><code># Check outdated packages
pip list --outdated

# Interactive update tool (prompts for each package)
pip install pip-review
pip-review --interactive    # review each update
pip-review --auto           # update everything automatically

# Security-focused: check for known CVEs
pip install pip-audit
pip-audit                   # scan for vulnerabilities
pip-audit --fix             # auto-upgrade vulnerable packages

# Poetry users
poetry show --outdated
poetry update               # update to latest within constraints
poetry update requests      # update specific package

# pip-tools: regenerate lockfile from high-level requirements
pip install pip-tools
pip-compile requirements.in  # produces requirements.txt with pinned versions
pip-sync requirements.txt    # sync venv to exactly match lockfile</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3">Dependabot &amp; Renovate Configuration</h2>
      <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">Automate dependency updates entirely. Dependabot is the zero-config choice for GitHub. Renovate gives you fine-grained control — grouping packages, automerge rules, and custom schedules.</p>
      <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm font-mono text-gray-300"><code># .github/dependabot.yml — Dependabot configuration
version: 2
updates:
  - package-ecosystem: "npm"
    directory: "/"
    schedule:
      interval: "weekly"
      day: "monday"
    groups:
      eslint:
        patterns: ["eslint*", "@typescript-eslint/*"]
    ignore:
      - dependency-name: "some-legacy-package"
        versions: [">=2.0.0"]

  - package-ecosystem: "github-actions"
    directory: "/"
    schedule:
      interval: "monthly"

# renovate.json — Renovate Bot configuration (more powerful)
&#123;
  "$schema": "https://docs.renovatebot.com/renovate-schema.json",
  "extends": ["config:base"],
  "automerge": true,
  "automergeType": "pr",
  "packageRules": [
    &#123;
      "matchUpdateTypes": ["minor", "patch"],
      "automerge": true
    &#125;,
    &#123;
      "matchUpdateTypes": ["major"],
      "automerge": false,
      "labels": ["breaking-change"]
    &#125;,
    &#123;
      "matchPackagePatterns": ["^react"],
      "groupName": "React packages"
    &#125;
  ]
&#125;</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Major vs Minor Update Risk Assessment</h2>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-700">
              <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 text-gray-300 font-semibold">Update Type</th>
              <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 text-gray-300 font-semibold">Example</th>
              <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 text-gray-300 font-semibold">Risk Level</th>
              <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 text-gray-300 font-semibold">Recommended Approach</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-700/50 hover:bg-gray-800/30">
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-300">Patch (x.x.N)</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">1.2.3 → 1.2.4</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-green-400">Low</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Automerge if CI passes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-700/50 hover:bg-gray-800/30">
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-300">Minor (x.N.0)</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">1.2.3 → 1.3.0</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-yellow-400">Medium</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Automerge with full CI; review if large</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-700/50 hover:bg-gray-800/30">
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-300">Major (N.0.0)</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">1.2.3 → 2.0.0</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-red-400">High</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Read migration guide; manual review</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-700/50 hover:bg-gray-800/30">
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-300">Security patch</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Any version with CVE</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-red-400">Critical</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Apply immediately; same-day if critical CVE</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="hover:bg-gray-800/30">
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-300">Pre-release</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">2.0.0-beta.1</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-red-400">Very High</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-400">Never automerge; use only for testing</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

  </div>

  <FaqSection faq={faq} />
</BaseLayout>
